We recommended that Management require the Municipal Accountant to:

a. Exert more effort to locate pertinent supporting documents and prepare subsidiary ledgers for the receivable accounts based thereon;
b. Assess/evaluate the condition of all dormant receivables in order to determine whether which are still recoverable and/or which are subject to possible write-off;
1) For receivables determined to be recoverable, exhaust all possible remedies to enforce collection thereof.  Likewise, issue demand letters to the identified NGAs and NGOs/POs to immediately liquidate the funds transferred to them;
2)For receivables determined to be beyond recovery in consonance with COA Circular No. 2016-005, facilitate the filing of request for authority to write-off following the guidelines and procedures set forth in the Circular.  Also, recognize impairment for accounts no longer collectible pursuant to the aforementioned accounting standards;

c. Ensure documentation, regular monitoring and analysis of receivable accounts to ensure prompt collection thereof when these become due and demandable, liquidation of fund transfers within the prescribed period depending on their nature and purpose, and to prevent further accumulation of dormant accounts.

